                    <msContents>
                        <textLang mainLang="la"/>
                        <msItem class="#funerary.epitaph">
                            <p>Epitaph of Au. Pompeius Au.l. Hilarus and Cn. Pompeius Cn.l. Hilarus</p>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc ana="#slab">
                            <supportDesc ana="#stone.marble">
                                <support>
                                    <p>
                                        <seg type="material">white marble</seg> 
                                        <seg type="form">broken slab</seg>
                                    </p>
                                    <dimensions type="surface" unit="cm">
                                        <width>38.5</width>
                                        <height>14.0</height>
                                        <depth>3.5</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition ana="#fragment.single">
                                    <p>A thick circular hole has been bored in the centre of the lefthand border. The stone is broken at right, inside the border, without loss of text, perhaps where a matching hole had been bored.</p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout columns="1" writtenLines="3">
                                    <p>The text appears to have been centred, but it is unclear whether or not the mason ran out of room in the top and bottom lines.</p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc ana="#impressed.inscribed.chiseled">
                            <handNote><p>N.b. AV ligatures to represent the praenomen Aulus throughout. The small circle at the end of the first and last lines is confusing, because the cognomen Hilario is attested; on balance this seems more likely to be decorative (cf. the border) rather than implying Hilario(nis). This follows the reading by Bodel and Tracy (1997), p. 156, i.e. "epitaph of Au. Pompeius Au.l. Hilarus (et al.)".
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote ana="border">
                                <p>Text surrounded by incised line border. The thin rectangles that this border created to the left and right of the central panel with the text have been bisected across their middle, and incised with crossing oblique lines to create triangles. The top border has been incised with a long oblique line sloping downwards from the top corner to meet at the middle, where a small, shallow V has been incised above the I of Pompei.</p>
                            </decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <summary>In <bibl><ptr target="Olcott_Catalogue"/>a handwritten catalogue</bibl> in Butler library George N. Olcott records this inscription as coming "From Via Salaria, as the preceding" (i.e. NY.NY.CU.Butl.L.34).</summary>
                        <origin>
